don't know what

31:54.153 --> 31:59.259
they did. How did you get along with the conquered 
enemy? We didn't have any problems. No problems

32:05.227 --> 32:07.990
with the Germans? No. Except we had problems with 
BD. What were the feelings toward the Germans?

32:27.963 --> 32:29.785
Well, we weren't particularly hostile. We 
thought they

32:29.885 --> 32:34.911
were a victim of hit and run. And I can remember when 
I first went with the 12th Tactical Air Command, my

32:34.931 --> 32:46.464
friend and I moved into a doctor's house. He left 
everything there.

32:55.114 --> 32:55.434
We just went in. We never saw him.

33:01.763 --> 33:06.770
It didn't last long, but it was quite nice. And our 
quarters at Swineford were very good, too. Of

33:12.178 --> 33:17.426
course, that place had been beaten up. We had 
bombed that several times, but we put in our own

33:18.968 --> 33:24.777
runway. There was still a plank runway. Some of the 
barracks were undamaged and used then.

33:31.733 --> 33:44.346
When you heard that the United States dropped the 
atomic bomb and that the war in the Pacific was

33:31.733 --> 33:44.346
over, how did you feel about that?

33:44.366 --> 33:50.892
Well, I was glad to hear it was

33:44.366 --> 33:50.892
over. I think we all were. It was a relief, too. Yet 
at the same time, now you wouldn't be able to have

33:52.954 --> 33:56.678
more combat missions. Well, that wasn't going to 
bother me. It was over.

34:12.609 --> 34:16.074
That's not to say that I want to go out and apply 
combat. Just apply combat. I don't. It's scary.

34:22.463 --> 34:24.626
It's not... It's not... I think it's hazardous to 
your health. Yeah, that's right. It's surgeon

34:29.901 --> 34:32.584
general, like I said. I got shot up, I guess, at 
least 15 times. You did? Yeah. Shot down once,

34:39.992 --> 34:44.096
but shot up. Do you consider yourself lucky? Very

34:46.258 --> 34:51.944
lucky. Extremely lucky. Were you, besides your 
nose,

34:58.083 --> 35:13.857
During

34:58.083 --> 35:13.857
this time, 1945 to 1947, America's armed forces 
dwindled from 12 million down to a million and a

34:58.083 --> 35:13.857
half. Rapid demobilization. Explosive 
demobilization, I'd say. That was the situation

35:20.644 --> 35:22.505
in Germany. The rail was low, and people had lots of 
points. He had morale problems like what I

35:28.255 --> 35:34.401
did. Farmed a football team.

35:38.684 --> 35:42.067
A classmate of mine at this point now that coaches. 
We won the USA championship. No kidding. We had a

35:44.870 --> 35:47.372
lot of fun. So in other words, you directed 
sporting events. Yeah. Well, we had other things

35:52.637 --> 35:55.860
too. We got him the permission to go deer hunting. 
Really? Yeah. We shot a lot of deer. Where'd they

36:01.874 --> 36:02.455
go? They went in the woods. There were lots of woods 
in town. Oh, yeah. And lots of deer.

36:10.506 --> 36:11.568
We enjoyed venison, too. For officers and men? 
Yeah. Did you set up an officer's club and EM club?

36:18.298 --> 36:18.638
Oh, yes. They had nice... And they also had Red 
Cross clubs. Did you try to bring in movies or movie

36:24.186 --> 36:26.529
stars? We had movies.

36:32.245 --> 36:33.607
And then we started there. We had B.B. Daniels at 
the Pond Tarsen right after B. Day. We had Spike

36:38.893 --> 36:47.984
Jones stayed with us at Pond Tarsen for just a 
couple of weeks. And they went out to the various

36:48.145 --> 36:52.390
Army units. Of course, we were Army too then. And 
played for them and played for us at our club. And

36:58.497 --> 36:58.978
they stood in. We set up an officer's club and an 
enlisted man's club everywhere we went. We did it

37:05.199 --> 37:09.145
with a tent.

37:10.547 --> 37:12.450
As far as... Good for morale. Sure. And did you 
actually feel that you increased more? Yes. We had

37:19.240 --> 37:23.185
hires for you in our organization, Michael. Very 
much. All your friends and a lot of the associates

37:25.909 --> 37:28.493
and a lot of pilots

37:33.468 --> 37:34.729
back into civilian life. At any time did you feel 
that you wanted to go back into civilian life? None

37:40.255 --> 37:40.936
whatsoever. As a matter of fact, my father offered 
me the opportunity. He said before he wanted me to

37:45.300 --> 37:50.406
come in the business with me and my brother. He 
said, no, I want to stay in the

37:50.426 --> 37:54.510
airport. Thought I found a career. I enjoyed 
flying.

38:00.696 --> 38:01.517
I don't understand it. I thought

38:03.708 --> 38:12.621
it was an opportunity. It gave me an opportunity as 
a major to have a colonel's job. And I was on the list

38:16.987 --> 38:23.396
to be promoted to lieutenant colonel when the war 
ended. No, they didn't. No, they realized

38:26.561 --> 38:30.306
demobilization, they wouldn't need that many 
officers. Okay, so through 1946, until 1946, you

38:31.079 --> 38:41.875
were the deputy commander of 64th Fighter Wing? 
Well, that was a consolidation. It looks like it.

38:50.887 --> 38:56.115
It was a consolidation of the Fighter Wing and the 
group. And they just moved the Fighter Wing, which

38:56.135 --> 39:01.002
looked at a a town near there that moved them out 
there to the air base. And the wing ran the group, I

39:05.282 --> 39:20.564
mean ran the organization there, and also all the 
other fighter planes that were

39:05.282 --> 39:20.564
under. So it was just a... Well, there was a lot of 
consolidation at this time. They sent the 86

39:24.249 --> 39:28.896
fighter group home. and the people that were 
eligible to go, went. The rest of the regular

39:36.163 --> 39:50.485
officers that were there stayed,

39:36.163 --> 39:50.485
and the others that didn't have enough

39:36.163 --> 39:50.485
points to go. In 1946, though, you have a rather 
unusual assignment, which lasts from May 46 to

39:50.505 --> 39:57.516
September 47, and that's that the officers

40:00.905 --> 40:03.389
I was a master of the sword. Oh, what's a master of 
the sword? It's the physical education

40:08.536 --> 40:15.426
department. And what did you do there? This is kind 
of an unusual assignment for a fighter pilot.

40:28.917 --> 40:31.301
It wasn't the Air Force then, I was in the Army 
still. Yeah, sure, still the Army Air Corps. And

40:33.924 --> 40:42.377
West Point had pretty high priority on selecting 
who they wanted for instructors. And I was

40:42.397 --> 40:53.794
selected by the

40:42.397 --> 40:53.794
Director of Physical Education, if you will, or 
the Master of the Sword, to come there and be a...

40:54.753 --> 41:07.130
What I did, I came home on R&R expecting to go back to 
Germany and get a good job in the 64th Fighter Wing.

41:07.570 --> 41:16.102
But while I was home on R&R, my orders were changed 
and I was sent to West Point to be an instructor.

41:16.122 --> 41:17.183
What were your feelings about that? I was highly 
pissed off. I wanted to be, I got married, and I

41:20.437 --> 41:26.143
wanted to be the first guy back to Germany with his 
wife. And my classmate, one of my classmates did

41:27.605 --> 41:31.670
just that. He was the first guy to have his wife over 
there. Because by this time, the Army allowed

41:36.015 --> 41:39.659
people to have dependents. Yeah. But you could 
still have her at West Point. Oh, I did. Two of our

41:46.386 --> 41:47.828
children were born there. And she enjoyed 
wrestling.

41:53.734 --> 41:55.016
And I did enjoy it, too. But I did not want to get out 
of flying airplanes. And did you like instructing

42:01.422 --> 42:03.325
cadets? I enjoyed them. And physical education. 
Yeah, I know. But what type? I mean, what did you?

42:10.693 --> 42:12.474
Well, I taught wrestling. Wrestling. And I was on 
the wrestling team. I taught wrestling. I taught

42:19.972 --> 42:25.058
administration of athletic programs. I taught 
football coaching. I

42:26.840 --> 42:33.727
taught calisthenics. Why do you have an engineer 
teaching this? I wasn't an engineer. Well, true,

42:38.293 --> 42:47.683
you were an army officer, but you had an 
engineering background and a mathematical

42:38.293 --> 42:47.683
background.

42:53.452 --> 42:59.560
They select the instructors up there based on 
their records. I had played football and I coached

42:59.580 --> 43:10.053
football there in my last year

42:59.580 --> 43:10.053
as one of the coaches there. I played lacrosse and I 
played a lot of sports and of course

43:10.073 --> 43:17.603
the wrestling team.

43:22.510 --> 43:24.693
this was the type of person that he wanted. Now, is 
there any tension between the returning

43:25.774 --> 43:38.171
veterans, combat hardened veterans, and the new 
cadets who are just starting out at West Point? Any

43:38.191 --> 43:43.698
tension, or do they look up to you, or, you know, 
this is a peculiar time? No, because they had in

43:44.660 --> 43:50.307
the, they had in the, in the, in the Corps, they had 
guys that had had combat.

43:56.054 --> 43:57.756
And they were in the Corps. And they were looked up 
to. They really were. So they had individual

44:02.763 --> 44:14.198
people who had been enlisted men then who had gone 
to Europe and now they, after combat they had, they

44:02.763 --> 44:14.198
received appointments to West Point to start. 
Some of them had been, even one guy had been a

44:14.278 --> 44:18.203
captain. No kidding. And a pilot. Mm-hmm. But in 
the reserve.

44:28.665 --> 44:30.848
And then when he was commissioned, what did they 
commission him as? He had already been

44:31.028 --> 44:34.133
commissioned, so what did they commission him? He 
resigned that commission. He resigned the

44:35.434 --> 44:40.601
commission to go to... Well, he doesn't have to 
resign his reserve commission. He goes in as a vet.

44:43.265 --> 44:47.511
He still is a reserve captain.

44:47.531 --> 44:49.133
That's a peculiar situation. Yeah, it was a 
peculiar situation.

44:54.749 --> 44:56.131
They looked up to him. Yeah, they really did.

45:00.856 --> 45:12.309
During this time, of course, there was an attempt, 
which was successful, to separate the Army Air

45:00.856 --> 45:12.309
Corps from the Army and make it the Air Force. What 
were your feelings on this? I was elated. Why? I

45:17.375 --> 45:18.937
wanted to be separate from the Army. Well, you were 
a West Point graduate. That had nothing to do with

45:21.700 --> 45:24.503
it, in terms of air power. Because air power was 
subordinated to people who didn't know enough

45:24.803 --> 45:31.752
about it. And they proved that when they made the 
Joint Chiefs of Staff. Even during the war,

45:37.219 --> 45:51.638
the head of the Air Corps was made General of the Air 
Force, General Arnold.

45:54.908 --> 46:17.999
The three separate services, in my opinion, the 
Air Force should not be subordinated to the Army,

45:54.908 --> 46:17.999
because it goes beyond the Army, where the Army is 
not even involved in strategic bombing and so

45:54.908 --> 46:17.999
forth. So all of us that were in the Air Corps, Happy 
to serve

46:24.541 --> 46:33.918
in the Air

46:24.541 --> 46:33.918
Force. You just wanted your independence.

46:40.429 --> 46:43.394
And commanding and being under command yourself. 
Yeah, and being under commanders. Who were Air

46:47.341 --> 46:48.303
Corps people. Air Corps people and not Army. You 
were

46:49.972 --> 47:10.865
teaching at West Point at the time with a lot of Army 
officers who were not Air Corps types. What were

47:12.087 --> 47:15.152
the feelings toward this?

